{"title_page": "Alan Wall", "text_new": "'''Alan Wall''' is a British [[novelist]] and [[short story]] writer.\n\n==Biography==\nWall was born in [[Bradford]] and studied at the [[University of Oxford]]. After a variety of jobs, he became a full-time writer in his forties.<ref name=\"Rennison2005\">{{cite book|author=Nick Rennison|title=Contemporary British novelists|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mAjKQVAyJEgC&pg=PA172|accessdate=19 May 2013|year=2005|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-0-415-21708-8|pages=172\u2013}}</ref> In addition to his work as a professional author, he has developed a career teaching [[creative writing]] with posts at [[Liverpool John Moores University]], the [[University of Birmingham]] and the [[University of Chester]]. He is also a published [[poet]] and [[critic]]. He has a voice reminiscent if David Attenborough which he uses to hold the attention of his infatuated creative writing students.<ref>[http://www.chester.ac.uk/departments/english/staff/professor-alan-wall Staff page at University of Chester]</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{Expand list|date=May 2017}}\n\n===Books===\nJacob 1993 (Poetry)\n*{{cite book |author=Wall, Alan |authorlink= |authormask= |title=Curved light |location= |publisher= |year=1994 |<!--isbn=-->}}\n*''Bless the Thief'' (1997)\n*''Silent Conversations'' (1998)\n*''The Lightning Cage'' (1999)\n*''[[The School of Night#In culture|The School of Night]]'' (2001)\n*''China'' (2003)\n*''Sylvie's Riddle'' (2008)\n*''Badmouth'' (2014)\n\n=== Short fiction ===\n{|class='wikitable sortable' width='90%'\n|-\n!width=25%|Title\n!|Year\n!|First published\n!|Reprinted/collected\n!|Notes\n|-\n|Spider god and the periodic table\n|2013\n|{{cite journal |author=Wall, Alan |authorlink= |authormask= |date=Apr\u2013May 2013 |title=Spider god and the periodic table |department= |journal=Asimov's Science Fiction |volume=37 |issue=4&5 |pages=108\u2013135}}\n| \n|Novelette\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*[htt