{"title_page": "Alan Uger", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name   = Alan Uger\n| image  = \n| caption = \n| birth_name = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|1940|12|24|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = \n| death_date  = \n| death_place = New York City, New York, U.S.\n| nationality = \n| occupation  = writer, film producer\n| years_active  = 1972\u20131996\n| spouse = \n}}\n'''Alan Uger''' is an [[Emmy|Emmy-winning]] writer and producer, known for [[Family Ties]], [[Blazing Saddles]], and [[Champs (TV series)|Champs]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0880078/|title=Alan Uger|website=IMDb|access-date=2019-10-21}}</ref> He was nominated three times for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Writing for a Comedy Series|Outstanding Writer in a Comedy Series]] for Family Ties, in 1985\u20137, winning in 1987.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.emmys.com/bios/alan-uger|title=Alan Uger|website=Television Academy|language=en|access-date=2019-10-21}}</ref> Between 1972 and 1996 Al wrote or produced dozens of TV show episodes or screenplays. Uger was also nominated for [[BAFTA]] and [[Writers Guild of America West|WGA]] awards.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Uger, Alan}}\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:American male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Male television writers]]\n[[Category:American television writers]]\n[[Category:Emmy Award winners]]\n[[Category:American producers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n\n{{US-tv-writer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name   = Alan Uger\n| image  = \n| caption = \n| birth_name = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|1940|12|24|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = \n| death_date  = \n| death_place = New York City, New York, U.S.\n| nationality = \n| occupation  = writer, film producer\n| years_active  = 1972\u20131996\n| spouse = \n}}\n'''Alan Uger''' is an [[Emmy|Emmy-winning]] writer and producer, known for [[Family Ties]], [[Blazing Saddles]], and [[Champs (TV series)|Champs]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0880078/|title=Alan Uger|website=IMDb|access-date=2019-10-21}}</ref> He was nominated three times for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Writing for a Comedy Series|Outstanding Writer in a Comedy Series]] for Family Ties, in 1985\u20137, winning in 1987.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.emmys.com/bios/alan-uger|title=Alan Uger|website=Television Academy|language=en|access-date=2019-10-21}}</ref> Between 1972 and 1996 Al wrote or produced dozens of TV show episodes or screenplays. Uger was also nominated for [[BAFTA]] and [[Writers Guild of America West|WGA]] awards.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Uger, Alan}}\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:American male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Male television writers]]\n[[Category:American television writers]]\n[[Category:Emmy Award winners]]\n[[Category:American producers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n\n{{US-tv-writer-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alan_Uger"}
{"title_page": "2020 BDO World Darts Championship", "text_new": "{{Infobox individual darts tournament\n| tournament_name = BDO World Darts Championship\n| image           =\n| dates           = 4\u201312 January 2020\n| venue           = [[The O2#indigo at The O2|Indigo at The O2]]\n| location        = [[London]]\n| country         = [[England]], [[United Kingdom]]\n| organisation    = [[British Darts Organisation|BDO]]\n| format          = [[Set (darts)|Sets]]\n| prize_fund      = \u00a3127,000 ''(men)''<br />\u00a326,500 ''(women)''\n| winners_share   = \u00a323,000 ''(men)''<br />\u00a310,000 ''(women)''\n| nine_dart       = \n| high_checkout   = {{nowrap|1='''170''' {{flagicon|NED}} [[Martijn Kleermaker]] (x2)}}<br />{{nowrap|1={{0|'''170'''}} {{flagicon|NED}} [[Chris Landman]]}}<br />{{nowrap|1={{0|'''170'''}} {{flagicon|NED}} [[Willem Mandigers]]}}\n| winner          = {{flagicon|WAL}} [[Wayne Warren]] (men)<br />{{flagicon|JPN}} [[Mikuru Suzuki]] (women) <br />{{flagicon|IRL}} [[Keane Barry]] (youth)\n| prev            = [[2019 BDO World Darts Championship|2019]]\n| next            = <!--[[2021 BDO World Darts Championship|2021]]-->\n}}\n\nThe '''2020 Bad Darts Organisation World Professional Darts Championship''' was the 43rd [[BDO World Darts Championship|World Championship]] organised by the British Darts Organisation, and the 1st staging at the [[The O2#indigo at The O2|Indigo at The O2]] in [[London]]. It was the first [[BDO World Darts Championship]] not held at the [[Lakeside Leisure Complex|Lakeside Country Club]] since [[1985 BDO World Darts Championship|1985]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/darts/49212214|title=BDO World Championships to leave Lakeside venue in 2020|last=|first=|date=29 October 2019|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n[[Gabriel Pascaru]] and [[Thibault Tricole]] became the first players from [[Romania]] and [[France]] respectively to play in a [[World Darts Championship]]. \n\nThree-time men's defending champion [[Glen Durrant]] was absent from the event, having switched to the [[Professional Darts Corporation]] in January 2019. \n\nThe reigning women's champion was [[Mikuru Suzuki]]. She successfully retained her title, by defeating [[Lisa Ashton]] 3\u20130 in the final.\n\n[[Wayne Warren]] won his first world title with a 7\u20134 win over fellow Welshman [[Jim Williams (darts player)|Jim Williams]] in the final. He became the oldest player ever to win a world title.\n\n== Prize money ==\nOn 30 December 2019, less than a week before the tournament was due to start, it was announced that due to ticket sales of only 15%, the prize money would be 'reduced somewhat'.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/darts/50952382 | title=BDO World Championship prize money 'reduced somewhat' after poor ticket sales| work=BBC Sport| date=2019-12-30}}</ref>. A reduction from \u00a3359,000 to \u00a3150,000 was reported in the media but prize money aside from the winners was unconfirmed.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2019/dec/31/fallon-sherrock-withdraws-bdo-world-darts-prize-money | title=Fallon Sherrock pulls out of women's BDO world darts after prize money is cut| newspaper=The Guardian| date=2019-12-31| last1=Sport| first1=Guardian| last2=Media| first2=P. A.}}</ref>. It was thought that the prize money would be reduced by half in most cases, although this was unconfirmed.\n\nOn 15 January 2020, the prize fund was finally revealed with the men's champion portion dropping from \u00a3100,000 last year to only \u00a323,000 this year<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://dartsnews.com/reduced-prize-fund-for-2020-bdo-world-championship-finally-revealed/|title=Reduced prize fund for 2020 BDO World Championship finally revealed|last=Gill|first=Samuel|date=15 January 2020|url-status=live|publisher=Darts News}}</ref>.\n\nOn 11 February 2020, it was reported that players had still not received any prize money, despite payment being due by 9 February, 28 days after the tournament ended.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/02/11/bdo-world-championship-prize-money-still-not-paid-as-28-day-deadline-passes-12220330/|title=BDO World Championship prize money still not paid as 28-day deadline passes|last=Haigh|first=Phil|date=11 February 2020|url-status=live|publisher=Metro}}</ref>.\n\n'''Men's'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"2\" |Position <small>(num. of players)</small>\n!Prize money\n|-\n|'''Winner'''\n| align=\"center\" |<small>(1)</small>\n| align=\"center\" |\u00a323,000\n|-\n|'''Runner-up''' \n| align=\"center\" |<small>(1)</small>\n| align=\"center\" |\u00a310,000\n|-\n|'''Semi-finalist'''\n| align=\"center\" |<small>(2)</small>\n| align=\"center\" |\u00a35,000\n|-\n|'''Quarter-finalist'''\n| align=\"center\" |<small>(4)</small>\n| align=\"center\" |\u00a34,000\n|-\n|'''Second round losers'''\n| align=\"center\" |<small>(8)</small>\n| align=\"center\" |\u00a33,000\n|-\n|'''First round losers'''\n| align=\"center\" |<small>(16)</small>\n| align=\"center\" |\u00a32,000\n|-\n|'''Preliminary round losers'''\n| align=\"center\" |<small>(8)</small>\n| align=\"center\" |\u00a31,500\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\" |\n|-\n|'''Total'''\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" |\u00a3127,000\n|}\n\n'''Women's'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"2\" |Position <small>(num. of players)</small>\n!Prize money\n|-\n|'''Winner'''\n| align=\"center\" |<small>(1)</small>\n| align=\"center\" |\u00a310,000\n|-\n|'''Runner-up'''\n| align=\"center\" |<small>(1)</small>\n| align=\"center\" |\u00a34,500\n|-\n|'''Semi-finalist'''\n| align=\"center\" |<small>(2)</small>\n| align=\"center\" |\u00a32,000\n|-\n|'''Quarter-finalist'''\n| align=\"center\" |<small>(4)</small>\n| align=\"center\" |\u00a31000\n|-\n|'''First round losers'''\n| align=\"center\" |<small>(8)</small>\n| align=\"center\" |\u00a3500\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\" |\n|-\n|'''Total'''\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" |\u00a326,500\n|}\n\n==Men's=